[[simple:Tenjinja]] {{Shrine | Name = Tenjinsha (天神社) | image = {{image requested|cat=Kazo City}} | location = {{ill|Hiranaga, Kazo, Saitama|ja|平永|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kazo, Saitama|ja|加須市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|12=draft|12=draft}}, 1197 | coordinates = {{Coord|36|07|44.2|N|139|33|30.0|E|display=title}} | deity = {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft|12=draft}} | Shrine Rank = Village Shrine (村社) | Established = First year of {{ill|Genna era|ja|元和|12=draft|12=draft}}, 1615 | Main Hall = | Other Names = | Pilgrimage Route = | Annual Festival = | Rituals = }}
'''Tenjinsha''' (天神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kazo, Saitama|ja|加須市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History ==
The shrine was founded in 1615, during the first year of the {{ill|Genna era|ja|元和|12=draft|12=draft}}. A retainer of {{ill|Sakakibara Yasumasa|ja|榊原康政|12=draft|12=draft}}, the first lord of the {{ill|Tatebayashi Domain|ja|館林藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, named Matsuzaki Kanbee (松崎勘兵衛), was known for his scholarly excellence and virtue. Recognizing his abilities, Yasumasa presented him with a hanging scroll of {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft|12=draft}}, inscribed by {{ill|Emperor Go-Yōzei|ja|後陽成天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. Later, local villagers, inspired by their reverence for both Michizane and Kanbee, established the shrine.
In 1766 (the 3rd year of the {{ill|Meiwa era|ja|明和|12=draft|12=draft}}), the shrine was reconstructed, and at that time, the Matsuzaki family donated the Sugawara no Michizane scroll to the shrine. The neighboring {{ill|Jōsen-in (Kazo)|ja|常泉院|12=draft|12=draft}} served as the shrine's {{ill|bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|12=draft|12=draft}} (guardian temple).<ref name="shrine">Saitama Shrine Office Research Group, *Shrines of Saitama: Iruma, North Saitama, and Chichibu* (『埼玉の神社 入間・北埼玉・秩父』), Saitama Shrine Office, 1986, pp. 890-891.</ref>
In 1876 (9th year of the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}}), the shrine was officially designated as a "Village Shrine" (村社) under the {{ill|Modern shrine ranking system|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft|12=draft}}. After World War II, the shrine's significance gradually declined, but in 1975 (50th year of the {{ill|Shōwa era|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft}}), the local parishioners resolved to preserve it, leading to gradual restoration efforts.<ref name="shrine"></ref>
== Access ==
* 15 minutes by car from {{ill|Kazo Interchange|ja|加須インターチェンジ|12=draft|12=draft}} on the expressway.
